    readTime: "8 min read",
    content: `New York State Rifle and Pistol Association v. Bruen (full opinion: https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/20-843) was a landmark 2022 Supreme Court decision that fundamentally changed the legal framework courts use to evaluate firearms regulations. If you own or carry firearms, or if you follow gun law debates, understanding Bruen is essential.

## What the case was about

The case challenged New York's concealed carry licensing law, which required applicants to demonstrate "proper cause" for needing a concealed carry permit. In practice, this meant applicants had to show a specific, documented threat to their personal safety beyond the general desire for self-defense. Most applicants in New York City and many other jurisdictions were denied.

The Supreme Court ruled 6-3 that New York's "proper cause" requirement violated the Second and Fourteenth Amendments. The opinion, written by Justice Thomas, established that the government may not prevent law-abiding citizens from carrying handguns in public for self-defense.

## The new legal test

Before Bruen, most federal courts used a two-step framework to evaluate gun laws. First, they asked whether the regulated conduct fell within the scope of the Second Amendment. If it did, they applied some form of means-end scrutiny, usually intermediate scrutiny, which asked whether the law was substantially related to an important government interest.

Bruen replaced this with a historical test. Under the new framework, when someone challenges a firearms regulation, the government must justify the law by showing it is consistent with the historical tradition of firearms regulation in the United States. The relevant historical period centers on the Founding era (1791, when the Second Amendment was ratified) and Reconstruction (1868, when the Fourteenth Amendment was ratified).

## What this means in practice

The practical effect has been significant. Dozens of firearms regulations have been challenged under the Bruen framework, and courts have reached varying conclusions depending on whether they can find historical analogues for the specific type of regulation being challenged.

Laws that have been upheld under Bruen generally include prohibitions on firearms possession by convicted felons, restrictions on carrying in certain sensitive places like courthouses and polling places, and some licensing requirements that do not give officials discretion to deny permits to qualified applicants.

Laws that have been struck down or are under serious challenge include may-issue permitting schemes in states like New Jersey, Maryland, and Hawaii that functioned similarly to New York's system, some state-level assault weapons bans, and certain magazine capacity restrictions.

## The ongoing uncertainty

Bruen created a new framework but did not resolve every question. Lower courts are still working through what counts as a sufficient historical analogue, how broadly or narrowly to define the historical tradition, and how to handle modern weapons and regulations that have no precise historical equivalent. The result is significant ongoing litigation and some inconsistency between different federal circuits.`
